3.  Cellulosic  Ethanol  Specialist  (1  person-month).  The  consultant  will  undertake  the 
following activities for component 2: 

(i)  act as the technical lead responsible for component 2’s implementation;  
(ii)  work  closely  with  the  national  consultant  to  coordinate  the  preparation  and 
submission of the cellulosic ethanol technology assessment report;  
(iii)  outline  current  international  practices  and  PRC  experience  in  cellulosic  ethanol 
technology introduction and development;  
(iv)  assess advantages of cellulosic ethanol technology over other ethanol technologies;  
(v)  assess the current status of cellulosic ethanol technology, and anticipated advances;  
(vi)  assess barriers to cellulosic ethanol technology introduction in PRC;  
(vii)  assess  relative  advantages  for  cellulosic  ethanol  production  development  by 
biomass power generation facilities, and discuss international experience; and 
(viii)  provide recommendations for overcoming barriers to cellulosic ethanol technology 
introduction to PRC, including (a) policy and regulatory support, (b) capacity-building 
requirements, (c) methods to lower technology costs, (d) further areas of research 
and development required, and (e) financing requirements for future developments. 

4.  Biomass Feedstock Market Analyst (2 person-months). The consultant will undertake 
the following activities for Component 2: 

(i)  act as the technical lead responsible for the study and report on commodity market 
analysis for biomass power generation feedstock;  
(ii)  work closely with the national consultant to coordinate report submission;  
(iii)  visit operational biomass power plants to assess influences on market pricing; 
(iv)  summarize  international  experience  in  biomass  pricing  trends  during  the 
development phase of the biomass power generation sector, and provide suitable 
case studies of similar international markets; 
(v)  summarize international experience in commodity trends in established markets; 
(vi)  identify  suitable  pilot  biomass  power  generation  projects  in  PRC,  and  analyze 
experience of feedstock pricing fluctuations in detail; 
(vii)  identify several typical localized biomass feedstock markets in PRC that reflect the 
major types of feedstocks;  
(viii)  assess major pricing risks for these markets, including (a) supply contract risks, (b) 
transportation and storage risks, (c) pricing risks, (d) competitive use risks, and (e) 
regulatory and policy risks; 
(ix)  based on international experience, provide recommendations for major market risks; 
(x)  provide short- medium term biomass pricing trend projections for selected markets; 
(xi)  develop suitable methodologies for feedstock pricing projections; 
(xii)  assess pricing assumptions of selected operational biomass power plants against 
market projections; and 
(xiii)  act as a resource speaker for the biomass conference.  

5.  Biomass Resource Assessment Specialist (1.5 person-months). The consultant will 
undertake the following activities in support of Component 3:

Appendix 3  11 

(i)  act as the technical lead responsible for component 3’s implementation and report 
preparation;  
(ii)  visit operational biomass power plants in the province of Heilongjiang to review 
biomass resource assessment methodologies being implemented; 
(iii)  interact closely with component 1 consultants, and utilize lessons learned;  
(iv)  work closely with the EA to review existing resource assessment methodologies; 
(v)  work  closely  with  the  Heilongjiang  provincial  government  and  national  biomass 
resource specialists to design a biomass resource assessment for the province, and 
incorporate a sensitivity analysis suitable for replication in other provinces;  
(vi)  incorporate international resource assessment techniques into the design; 
(vii)  work  closely  with  the  Heilongjiang  provincial  government  to  identify  detailed 
requirements for biomass power generation strategy development;  
(viii)  analyze strategies developed in other provinces, and utilize relevant components; 
(ix)  prepare a draft Heilongjiang biomass power generation strategy; and 
(x)  work  closely  with  national  consultants  to  prepare  component  3’s  reporting 
deliverables, i.e., the biomass resource assessment and biomass power generation 
strategy for Heilongjiang. 

B.  National Consultants 

6.  Biomass  Power  Generation  Specialist  (7  person-months).  The  consultant  will 
undertake the following activities in support of component 1:  

(i)  coordinate component 1’s data collection activities and reporting among the national 
consultants, and ensure activities are carried out on schedule;  
(ii)  act  as  the  focal  point  between  project  sites,  EA,  national  consultants,  and 
governmental officials;  
(iii)  conduct site visits to at least three operational biomass power plants to assess 
lessons learned and implementation barriers; 
(iv)  consult  with  stakeholders  to  assess  barriers  to  biomass  power  generation  and 
lessons learned from existing projects;  
(v)  assess barriers and lessons learned for biomass power generation implementation, 
and work closely with the EA to determine report contents, including items in para. 1;   
(vi)  provide  specific  recommendations  for  overcoming  barriers  to  biomass  power 
generation  sector  development,  including  required  policy  and  regulatory 
developments, and incorporate international experience; 
(vii)  undertake a cost benefit analysis for biomass power plant development; 
(viii)  coordinate the biomass power generation steering committee, identify appropriate 
members, and coordinate and chair three meetings during TA implementation; 
(ix)  work closely with the EA to design and carry out two consultation workshops with 
government officials and two consultation workshops with the financial sector;  
(x)  act as a resource speaker for the biomass conference; and 
(xi)  prepare and submit workshop and conference activity reports.  

7.  Financial  Analyst  (2  person-months).  The  consultant  will  undertake  the  following 
activities in support of component 1: 

(i)  assess barriers to financing biomass power generation projects;  
(ii)  analyze financial risks and lessons learned from pilot biomass power plants;  
(iii)  provide recommendations for addressing financial risks and financial barriers;

12   Appendix 3 

(iv)  summarize  benefits  available  from  carbon  financing  and  the  current  situation 
regarding CDM approval of biomass power plant projects, including (a) discussion of 
relevant  approved  methodologies,  (b)  international  situation  regarding  biomass 
power generation projects that have accessed CDM, (c) current status of projects 
that have been approved in PRC, and (d) analysis of certified emission reduction 
contribution to project finances; and  
(v)  act as a resource speaker for the technical workshops for financial institutions and 
the biomass conference, and assist in design of workshops’ technical content.  

8.  Safeguard  Specialist  (Environment/Social)  (1  person-month).  The  consultant  will 
undertake the following activities in support of component 1: 

(i)  quantify the environmental benefits from the pilot biomass projects, including (a) 
reduced air emissions from replaced coal-fired power generation, (b) reduced air 
emissions from biomass left to decompose in the field, and (c) reduced air emissions 
from biomass burned in fields;  
(ii)  extrapolate environmental benefits after development of the biomass power sector;  
(iii)  conduct surveys of benefits to farmers from pilot biomass power generation projects;  
(iv)  analyze  impact  to  poor  households  from  biomass  power  generation  projects, 
including direct employment and alternative income streams; 
(v)  provide relevant environmental and social cost and benefit data to the biomass 
power generation expert for the cost-benefit analysis; and 
(vi)  provide  recommendations  for  maximizing  social  benefits  from  biomass  power 
generation projects and minimizing negative social impacts.  

9.  Cellulosic Ethanol Specialist (4 person-months). The consultant will undertake the 
following activities for component 2: 

(i)  work  closely  with  the  international  cellulosic  ethanol  specialist  to  prepare  the 
cellulosic ethanol technology assessment report; 
(ii)  assess PRC experience in cellulosic ethanol technology development;  
(iii)  quantify advantages of cellulosic ethanol technology over alternative technologies;  
(iv)  assess the current status of cellulosic ethanol technology, and anticipated advances;  
(v)  assess current and proposed regulatory control of ethanol production in PRC and the 
implications for cellulosic ethanol technology; 
(vi)  assess barriers to cellulosic ethanol technology introduction in PRC and assess 
relative advantages for development by biomass power generation facilities; 
(vii)  provide recommendations for overcoming barriers to cellulosic ethanol technology 
introduction to PRC, including (a) policy and regulatory support, (b) capacity-building 
requirements, (c) methods to lower technology costs, (d) required areas of research 
and development, and (e) financing requirements for future developments; and 
(viii)  act as a resource speaker for the biomass conference.  

10.  Biomass Feedstock Market Analyst (4 person-months). The consultant will undertake 
the following activities for component 2: 

(i)  work closely with the international consultant to prepare and submit the commodity 
market analysis report for biomass power generation;  
(ii)  coordinate the collection of local sector- and project-specific data; 
(iii)  visit operational biomass power plants to assess operational influences; 
(iv)  assist in the analysis of international experience in biomass pricing trends;
